# Before running `git push`, ensure you have initialized a Git repository, added files, committed changes, and set up a remote repository.

![Git Workflow](https://via.placeholder.com/600x200?text=Git+Workflow)

## Steps to Push Changes to a Remote Repository

### 1. Initialize a Git repository (if not already done)
```bash
git init
```

### 2. Add files to the staging area
```bash
git add .
```

### 3. Commit the changes
```bash
git commit -m "Initial commit"
```

### 4. Add a remote repository
Replace `<your-repository-url>` with your repository URL.
```bash
git remote add origin <your-repository-url>
```

### 5. Push the changes to the remote repository
```bash
git push -u origin main
```

![Git Push](https://via.placeholder.com/600x200?text=Git+Push)